The numbers are written on a hexagonal grid in a spiral that begins with 1 at the centre.  
A convenient way to treat the grid is to use **axial coordinates** \((q , r)\).  
The coordinate of the centre is \((0,0)=1\).  
The six unit directions in axial coordinates are  

\[
E=(1,0),\; NE=(0,1),\; NW=(-1,1),\; W=(-1,0),\; SW=(0,-1),\; SE=(1,-1).
\]

--------------------------------------------------------------------

### 1.  Find the coordinates of the number \(2026\)

For a cell on ring number \(k\) the maximum integer on that ring is

\[
N(k)=1+3k(k+1) .
\]

The integer \(2026\) lies between

\[
N(25)=1+3\cdot25\cdot26=1951
\qquad\text{and}\qquad
N(26)=1+3\cdot26\cdot27=2107 ,
\]

so it is on ring \(k=26\).

The offset of a cell in a ring (index from \(0\) to \(6k-1\)) is  

\[
\text{offset}=2026-N(25)-1=2026-1951-1=74 .
\]

--------------------------------------------------------------------

### 2.  Determine the \((q,r)\) coordinates of that offset

The traversal of a ring starts at \(( k , 0 )\) – the “east” side – and proceeds
through the six sides.  
An offset in the “side‑2” part (south‑west side) is written

\[
\text{offset}=k+i ,\qquad i=0,\dots ,k-1 .
\]

For \(k=26\):

* offset\(0\): \((26,0)\),
* offset\(1\): \((25,1)\),
* ...
* offset\(20\): \((6,20)\).

So

\[
\text{offset }74 = 26 + 48 = 74
\]

comes from \(i=48\).  
Hence the coordinates of the number \(2026\) are

\[
(-21, 14).
\]

--------------------------------------------------------------------

### 3.  Find the six neighbouring cells

In axial coordinates the neighbours of \((q,r)\) are

\[
\begin{aligned}
E &: (q+1,r)\\
NE&: (q,r+1)\\
NW&: (q-1,r+1)\\
W &: (q-1,r)\\
SW&: (q,r-1)\\
SE&: (q+1,r-1) .
\end{aligned}
\]

Thus the neighbours of \((-21,14)\) are

| Neighbour | Axial coordinates |
|-----------|--------------------|
| \(E\)     | \((-20,14)\) |
| \(NE\)    | \((-21,15)\) |
| \(NW\)    | \((-22,15)\) |
| \(W\)     | \((-22,14)\) |
| \(SW\)    | \((-21,13)\) |
| \(SE\)    | \((-20,13)\) |

--------------------------------------------------------------------

### 4.  Convert each \((q,r)\) back to its integer value

For any \((q,r)\) let  

\[
k=\max(|q|,|r|,|s|), \qquad s=-q-r .
\]

The offset of a cell in ring \(k\) is

\[
\text{offset}=
  \begin{cases}
     k-q,          & \text{if } r=k\text{ or }r=k-q,\\[2mm]
     3k-r,         & \text{if } q=-k,\\[2mm]
     3k-r,         & \text{if } r+q=-k,\\[2mm]
     4k+q,         & \text{if } r=-k,\\[2mm]
     6k+r,         & \text{if } q=k.  
  \end{cases}
\]

With \(N(k-1)=1+3(k-1)k\), the integer value of a cell is

\[
\boxed{\;N(k-1)+\text{offset}+1\;}
\]

Now we calculate each neighbour:

| Neighbour | \(k\) | offset | integer |
|-----------|-------|--------|---------|
| \((-20,14)\) | 20 | 46 | \(1141+46+1=1188\) |
| \((-21,15)\) | 21 | 48 | \(1261+48+1=1310\) |
| \((-22,15)\) | 22 | 51 | \(1387+51+1=1439\) |
| \((-22,14)\) | 22 | 52 | \(1387+52+1=1440\) |
| \((-21,13)\) | 21 | 50 | \(1261+50+1=1312\) |
| \((-20,13)\) | 20 | 47 | \(1141+47+1=1189\) |

--------------------------------------------------------------------

### 5.  Sum of the six neighbours

\[
\begin{aligned}
S=&1188+1310+1439+1440+1312+1189\\
  =& 7878 .
\end{aligned}
\]

--------------------------------------------------------------------

\[
\boxed{7878}
\]
----
